text.text: A Guide to Marylebone

text.html: Marylebone - the urban river that flows between Hyde Park and Regents Park. The dwelling of Britain’s gentry and tourists brandishing Madame Toussauds memorabilia. The place you don’t go if you want a coffee under £4 but the place you do go if you want Viennese opulence, minimalist design cafes and fine dining at its finest. Come on Mr Marylebone, let’s have it large.

Best for... magazine reading and cinnamon buns

tip.text:
The folk behind the actual Monocle Magazine are behind this swish little cafe, so we went in with big expectations. Straight off the bat, the style of the place is a bit out the ordinary - Swedish blonde wood decked all over the place, combined with a minimalist Japanese feel. It's like if IKEA started selling sushi. We like it.

There are all kinds of Scandinavian and Japanese recipes on offer here, from breakfasts to sandwiches, and they get in Swedish cakes from Fabrique Bakery. Oh those cinnamon buns...

Best for... time travelling back to 20th century Vienna

tip.text:
If Austrians built a time machine, Fischer's would be it. A shiny, meat-filled, schnitzelly time machine. Looking like a luxurious cabin on the Orient Express, stepping inside feels like you're back in 1930's Vienna. Do yourself a favour; pop your top trouser button before you come in, because this is hearty comfort food. Wiener schnitzels, sausages stuffed with emmental, and a collection of strudels are practically mandatory to order.

There’s a small cover charge involved, and the atmosphere is pretty reserved, but when you’re dining in an episode of Poirot would you expect anything less?

Best for... a melt-in-the-mouth steak

tip.text:
We thought we knew what steak was all about, and then we rolled up to Boxcar and had our timbers shook with potentially the best steak we've ever tasted. Big words but it's how we feel, and you can't hide your feelings. Boxcar is a butcher, deli (look out for those pork pies) and a casual grill restaurant all in one well-to-do Marylebone townhouse, complete with dark blue tiles, sleek chairs and smokey smells.

Whilst they do breakfast bits and lunch during the day (featuring things like treacle-cured bacon baps and artisan coffee), we came in the evening for their casual dinner service and had our socks blown right off. The menu might be small (it's either the steak, burger or veggie burger) but you've got all you need right there. The 28 day sirloin steak melted in our mouths, whilst the Rib eye special they had left us in a happy daze, unable to say much beyond "this is so good". You need to try this.

Best for... delicious dining

tip.text:
There are excellent restaurants and then there's Carousel: a warm and welcoming spot that works on a rotating chef basis - just like... a carousel. Every week or so, top chefs (and we mean top of the top) from all over the world are invited to guest in the kitchen. So what flavours to expect really depends on who's in the kitchen, but it's always going to be a set menu of the fine-dining variety, and pretty much guaranteed to be damn delicious. At £40pp these dinners will either seem like a bargain of rip off depending on your foodie knowledge. But trust us, they're worth every penny.

And then there's lunch. Cooked up by in-house chefs (who have the most sociable hours of any chef ever), the meal covers a wide range of carefully curated options. We'd strongly recommend grabbing a table in the garden (if the sun is out) and letting the pros choose for you. For £25 a head, we ended up with all sorts of goodies - from crispy fish skin snacks and subtly sweet ceviche starters, to fresh pasta, succulent fish and heavenly veggies. The things these guys can do with the humble potato - it's erotic stuff.

text.text: There are excellent restaurants and then there's Carousel: a warm and inviting spot which basically invites a top chef to guest in the kitchen ever month on rotation, like a carousel. So what to expect on the menu really depends on who's in the kitchen but it's almost guaranteed to be something delicious. Drop by for lunch or book yourself up for the set menu dinner which comes in at around £40 pp. Do it.
Best for... a literary trip

tip.text:
If you're the type that falls in love easily then beware Daunt Books, Marylebone High St, because it is to book lovers what Channing Tatum or Beyonce are to most regular lovers: the pinnacle of beauty. This charming and elegant Edwardian bookshop is full of wonder and magic, from the long, oak galleries to the ever friendly and helpful booksellers.

Originally opened as a travel bookshop, Daunt books has wonderfully categorised literature throughout the store by nation (as well as your typical fiction and non-fiction sections), allowing you to explore literary canons by virtue of Geography. Take the stairs down to the basement floor for the likes of Asian and South American collections, from novellas to travel guides, or peruse the other corners of the planet over the ground and first floors respectively.

Best for... a cheap eat

tip.text:
Golden Hind has been on this spot for over 100 years doing one thing: serving Marylebone locals (and tourists) decent fish and chips. It's a no-frills affair inside evoking thoughts of a simpler time - before Britain realised interior design was a thing. That means basic lino tiles, white walls and standard wooden furniture.

The fish, meanwhile, comes iced from Grimsby in the form of cod, haddock, salmon, plaice, skate and scampi; either fried in groundnut oil or steamed with olive oil and oregano. It's good and substantial - not earth shattering - but lightly battered and with a decent amount of flavour. Keep an eye out for some very delectable fishcakes, mushy peas and our dessert pick: bread and butter pud. Our only grumble is that the prices are not quite as cheap as we've come to expect from F&C. This is Marylebone though.

text.text: Taking things back to the heyday of the fish supper, this chippy is one of the most talked about in London. It's been around for over 100 years and there's a pretty simple reason for that: it does fresh, succulent fish and the prices are low. But with great qualities, come great quantities of people, so watch out for the lunchtime rush.
Best for... celeb safari

tip.text:
With so much love about town for The Ivy, it only made sense to open the doors to another poshed-up diner. This all-day affair will accommodate for any appetite, serving up morning-saviour brunches, middleman lunches and mighty fine dinners.

Bad boy designer Martin Brudnizkihas got well and truly stuck in with the design again, so you can only imagine how pretty this place is - so much so you might not want to touch anything. Stuff the mains, we're going straight onto desserts with the Melting Chocolate Bombe dressed in Milk Foam, Vanilla Ice Cream, Honeycomb and Hot Salted Caramel Sauce. Follow up with classic cocktails.

Best for... grubby burgers

tip.text: While playing the association game, the words 'Burger' and 'Iceland' don't seem like a match made in heaven, but we are officially converts to the Icelandic way. There are no bewildering or exotic burger creations here, just good old beef, chicken and vege varieties...just as nature intended. The vibe is pretty casual and the focus is on the burgers, which is really how it ought to be. Definitely get the Steak Burger, which uses a blend of rump, rib-eye and fillet cuts, and look out for some particularly decent skinny fries.

Best for... eating cheese for breakfast, lunch and dinner

tip.text:
If you're after something cheesy and delicately spectacular, you can't go wrong with La Fromagerie - a local favourite in Marylebone and purveyors of all things dairy. Their breakfasts are consistently gooey and great - look out for their Farmhouse Spring Breakfast which comes with a variety of cheeses and some tasty saucisson. Lunch arrives in the shape of soups, sandwiches and the cheese and charcuterie boards which have made this place famous. You ought to pair that with some of their wine too. It's simply the French way.

It's often pretty busy here, and you'll be lucky to get yourself a seat at lunch, but come a little later in the day and tuck into some delicious French cuisine. Leave the calorie counter at home.

Best for... a taste of the Basque country

tip.text:
Meaning 'land' in Basque, Lurra is a Basque restaurant focused on serving well sourced, natural produce. They have their own wine and meat importing business and even have a herb garden. The self-sufficient so-and-sos.

Using the traditional charcoal wood grills of the Basque country, there's plenty of grilled fish on the menu and some quality beef cuts: their Galician Rubia Gallega rib eye steaks are of a quality you won't be finding elsewhere. They've also got a private courtyard for sitting under the stars or shivering in the rain, depending on the season.

Best for... cocktails and escapism

tip.text: A drop-dead-gorgeous Georgian townhouse and treasure trove in Marylebone, Seymours Parlour at the Zetter Townhouse is the atmospheric home to superb cocktails and pretty decadent parties. Amid red velvet walls, wooden furniture and candlelight, this is the place for a bit of escapism. Though it will certainly leave a dent in the wallet.
